            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.79-80_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial"><del>80</del><add>79</add></fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Wednesday</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear John,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>How are you? I have been thinking about you and hoping that all is well with you. I got the records in the mail Monday. They should be delivered by the end of the week.</p>
                
                <p>About the pause before "Cedar straight....". Do you feel that it is too short? When I edited the tape I played <del>t</del><add>i</add>t over several times and decided not to put a piece of tape in to lengthen the pause because I was afraid the change in background noise would be more noticeable than the pause. I could have put one of the pauses in from the tape you had made at Lassiter's but that didn't occure<sic>occur</sic> to me until the master had been recut. Did you notice that they put it in bands th<del>a</del><add>i</add>s time? They cut both sides over but only char<del>d</del><add>g</add>ed me for one side which was nice of them, I thought.</p>
                
                <p>I will have a mailer printed now and send it out to the people on the list you sent. This list only goes up to Feb. of 1955. Do you think there is any way to get the addresses of your students from Sept. of 1955 up to the present? Of course it would not be necessary to get this semesters students because they have already been informed of the record. But I'm sure that you<sic>your</sic> more recent s<del>ut<unclear>n</unclear>d</del><add>tude</add>nts would also be interested in the record.</p>
                
                <p>I had the record listed in the Schwann Long Playing Record <del>c</del><add>C</add>atalog which appears in appro<del/><add>x</add>amately<sic>approximately</sic> 3800 reccord shops all over the country. It will be <del>s</del><add>l</add>isted in the July issue and I hope that it will bring in some sales.</p>
                
                <p>John, would you give me permission to start working <del><unclear>one</unclear></del> on an adaptation of "The Song of Three Friends" for the movies? I am trying to start a company to produce feature lenght<sic>length</sic> films and if I do get started would like very much to do "The Song of Three Friends." I think it is a natural for the movies. You know that I would stick as close to the original intent of the story as possible. Please let me know how <del>o</del><add>y</add>ou feel about this and if it is alright with you I will start work on it right away.</p>
                
                <p>Take care of yourself and let me know how you are.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Affectionately,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Sandy</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
